r envisage a society that always puts the health of citizens first: the ‘Health Society’. The time for dithering and tinkering has passed. Prevention of disease is a task for all branches of government – not just the NHS but also for every workplace, employer, community and citizen. The ‘Health Society’ means working in radically new ways to extend our healthy lives and sustainably increase national prosperity.Saving sick Britain follows the science and lays down a challenge to us all: are we ready to make the change required to end these modern plagues? In answering the question the book helps steer the reader towards rethinking what both 'prevention' and ‘health’ mean in modern Britain.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 3, Good health and well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical policyzGreat Britain. 0aPreventive health serviceszGreat Britain. 0aPublic healthzGreat Britain. 7aMEDICAL / Public Health.2bisacsh  aGood health and well-being.  acommon chronic disease burden.  adisease prevention.  aepidemiology.  ahealth and society.  ahealth innovation.  ainequality.  apolicy reform.  apublic health.  apublic policy.  asystems biology.1 aOllier, Bill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOllier, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYuille, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615230540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526152305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526152305/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles